{"parse":{"title":"Chrisom","pageid":5422532,"revid":772275658,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Anciently, a <b>chrisom</b>, or \"chrisom-cloth,\" was the face-cloth, or piece of linen laid over a child's head when he or she was <a href=\"/wiki/Baptism\" title=\"Baptism\">baptised</a> or christened. Originally, the purpose of the chrisom-cloth was to keep the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chrism\" title=\"Chrism\">chrism</a></i>, a consecrated oil, from accidentally rubbing off.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Robert_Nares_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Robert_Nares-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> With time, the word's meaning changed, to that of a white mantle thrown over the whole infant at the time of baptism. The term has come to refer to a child who died within a month after its baptism&#8212;so called for the chrisom cloth that was used as a <a href=\"/wiki/Shroud\" title=\"Shroud\">shroud</a> for it. Additionally, in London's Bills of Mortality, the term chrisom was used to refer to infants who died within a month after being born.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Robert_Nares_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Robert_Nares-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chrisom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Robert_Nares-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Robert_Nares_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Robert_Nares_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Nares, Robert (1859). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=vRRJAAAAcAAJ&amp;pg=PA160&amp;lpg=PA160&amp;dq=blount%27s+glossography+chrisom&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=oLiszihhcP&amp;sig=qXi1u2boFIA06A2HjG2l6h2tOD8&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=4jlsU4bEO4XdoATM44BQ&amp;ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q=blount&#39;s%20glossography%20chrisom&amp;f=false\"><i>A Glossary; or Collection of Words, Phrases, Names and Allusions to Customs, Proverbs, etc., Which Have Been Thought to Require Illustration in the Works of English Authors, Particularly Shakespeare and His Contemporaries</i></a>. London: John Russel Smith. p.&#160;160.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+Glossary%3B+or+Collection+of+Words%2C+Phrases%2C+Names+and+Allusions+to+Customs%2C+Proverbs%2C+etc.%2C+Which+Have+Been+Thought+to+Require+Illustration+in+the+Works+of+English+Authors%2C+Particularly+Shakespeare+and+His+Contemporaries.&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pages=160&amp;rft.pub=John+Russel+Smith&amp;rft.date=1859&amp;rft.aulast=Nares&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DvRRJAAAAcAAJ%26pg%3DPA160%26lpg%3DPA160%26dq%3Dblount%2527s%2Bglossography%2Bchrisom%26source%3Dbl%26ots%3DoLiszihhcP%26sig%3DqXi1u2boFIA06A2HjG2l6h2tOD8%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DX%26ei%3D4jlsU4bEO4XdoATM44BQ%26ved%3D0CCkQ6AEwAA%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Dblount%27s%2520glossography%2520chrisom%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AChrisom\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/12px-PD-icon.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"12\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/18px-PD-icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/24px-PD-icon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"196\" data-file-height=\"196\" />&#160;This article incorporates text from a publication now in the <a 